:: loc-lancaster-house-driveway {"position":"250,550","size":"150,100"}
The gravel driveway leading to the Lancaster house is lined with overgrown lilac bushes and ancient maple trees whose branches form a natural canopy overhead. The driveway curves gently as it approaches the farmhouse, with deep ruts worn by years of farm equipment and family vehicles. Stone markers at the entrance bear the house number, and a weathered mailbox with "Lancaster" painted in fading letters stands sentinel beside a rusted farm gate that's permanently propped open.
[[Main house porch->loc-mainhouse-porch-south]]

:: loc-mainhouse-porch-south {"position":"400,550","size":"150,100"}
The southern end of the wraparound porch faces the main driveway and serves as the primary entrance to the Lancaster farmhouse. Wooden steps painted white but now peeling lead up to the covered porch, which features traditional turned spindles and decorative brackets. Two old rocking chairs sit beside a small table where the morning newspaper is usually left, and hanging baskets with wilted plants sway gently in the breeze. The porch boards creak underfoot, and the ceiling is painted sky blue—a traditional Pennsylvania practice meant to ward off insects and evil spirits.
[[North porch->loc-mainhouse-porch-north]]
