:: loc-forest-clearing-firepits
Deep within the forest lies a circular clearing where three large fire pits are arranged in a triangular pattern. Each pit is carefully constructed from local fieldstone and filled with partially burned logs and kindling that never seems to fully turn to ash. The surrounding trees bear strange carvings—symbols that don't match any known language, carved deep enough to weep sap that has hardened into amber-colored tears. The ground around the pits is packed hard from many feet, and sometimes you can find small bones scattered in the ashes, too small to be human but too large to belong to any local wildlife.
<<return>>

:: loc-lancaster-machine-barn-driveway {"position":"250,700","size":"150,100"}
A separate gravel drive branches off from the main road, leading directly to the machine shed and barn area. This working driveway is wider than the house drive to accommodate large farm equipment, and the gravel is mixed with hay chaff and motor oil stains from decades of agricultural use. Tire tracks from tractors, combines, and trucks create permanent ruts in the earth, and the air carries the scent of diesel fuel and hay. Metal gates on either side can be closed to contain livestock when needed.
[[Machine shed->loc-machine-shed]]

:: loc-neighbors-mailbox {"position":"400,700","size":"150,100"}
At the eastern edge of the Lancaster property, a cluster of rural mailboxes marks the boundary with neighboring farms. The collection includes the Lancaster box alongside several others serving the scattered rural residences in the area. The mailboxes are mounted on a shared wooden post that leans slightly from years of wind and weather. Tall grass and wildflowers grow around the base, and a narrow dirt path leads from here toward the neighbor's property through a break in the fence line.
